<% content_for :title, "Making a good Quartet" %>
<% content_for :description, "What separates a great Connections-style puzzle from a frustrating one — the rules of thumb for building a Quartet worth playing." %>

<%# HowTo schema — a step-by-step AI engines can extract as a guide. %>
<% content_for :structured_data do %>
  <%= json_ld({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "HowTo",
    name: "How to make a good Connections-style puzzle",
    description: "The rules of thumb for building a fair, satisfying Quartet.",
    step: [
      { "@type": "HowToStep", name: "Be fair", text: "Make it hard to solve but obvious in hindsight — trap people with wordplay, not obscurity." },
      { "@type": "HowToStep", name: "One true group per word", text: "Every word should belong to exactly one group, even if it looks like it could fit elsewhere." },
      { "@type": "HowToStep", name: "Build the trap on purpose", text: "Lay out an obvious-looking group where one word actually belongs somewhere else." },
      { "@type": "HowToStep", name: "Ramp the difficulty", text: "Yellow easiest, then green, blue, and purple as the showpiece twist." },
      { "@type": "HowToStep", name: "Keep categories tight", text: "The connection should be specific enough that the four words are the only four that fit." }
    ]
  }) %>
<% end %>

<div class="l-container">
  <h1><%= multicolor("Making a good Quartet") %></h1>

  <p class="m-lede">
    Anyone can drop sixteen words in a box. Making a Quartet people actually enjoy
    solving is a craft — and it's mostly about being fair while being sneaky. Here's
    what separates the ones that get a "hell yeah" from the ones that get rage-quit.
  </p>

  <h2>The one rule that matters: be fair</h2>
  <p>
    A great puzzle is hard to solve but obvious in hindsight. When someone finally
    cracks a group, they should think "oh, <em>nice</em>" — not "there's no way I
    could've known that." If solving your puzzle requires trivia only you know, it's
    not clever, it's just locked. Trap people with wordplay, not obscurity.
  </p>

  <h2>Every word belongs to exactly one group</h2>
  <p>
    This is the big one. In a clean Quartet, each of the sixteen words has one
    correct home — even if it <em>looks</em> like it could live somewhere else. That
    "looks like it could fit" tension is the entire game. But if a word <em>truly</em>
    fits two groups, the puzzle is broken: the solver guesses right and still gets
    marked wrong. Before you publish, check every word against all four groups and
    ask "could this honestly go here too?" If yes, fix it.
  </p>

  <h2>Make the trap on purpose</h2>
  <p>
    The best puzzles bait you. Lay out four words that <em>seem</em> like an obvious
    group, but one of them actually belongs elsewhere and a sneakier word takes its
    place. That near-miss is what makes people groan and grin. The obvious four
    should almost never be the right four.
  </p>

  <h2>Build a difficulty ramp</h2>
  <p>
    Use the colors the way they're meant to be used. Yellow is the gentle one —
    a group most people get on the first read. Then green, then blue, and
    <strong>purple is your showpiece</strong>: the hidden connection, the pun, the
    "words that can precede CAKE," the twist people screenshot. If all four groups
    are the same difficulty, the puzzle feels flat. Give them a climb.
  </p>

  <h2>Tight categories beat clever-but-vague ones</h2>
  <p>
    "Types of pasta" is a category. "Things that are kind of Italian" is a fight
    waiting to happen. The connection should be specific enough that the four words
    are the <em>only</em> four that fit it. Vague categories make solvers feel cheated
    even when they're right.
  </p>

  <h2>A quick gut-check before you publish</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Are all sixteen words genuinely different? (No repeats — the game keys on the
      word itself.)</li>
    <li>Does each word have exactly one true group?</li>
    <li>Is there at least one deliberate trap — an obvious-looking group that's wrong?</li>
    <li>Do the four groups climb in difficulty, with purple as the payoff?</li>
    <li>Could a stranger solve it with wit instead of inside knowledge?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Nail those and you've got a Quartet worth sharing. Bonus: good puzzles earn
    ratings, and ratings are how the best ones rise to the top around here.
  </p>

  <p><%= link_to "Go build one →", new_puzzle_path %></p>
</div>
